We have amazing news!!!! The USDA has once again made breakfasts and lunches FREE to all our students, regardless if a student qualifies for free and reduced lunches! This program will begin immediately and is in effect until the end of December. Due to this change, we anticipate more students will take advantage of eating breakfast and/or lunch at school. Therefore, we are asking parents to complete this survey (one per household) in order to make sure we have enough food to prepare next week.

With IESA reversing their decision regarding sports activities, tryouts/practice dates are below. Please review the guidelines as well.

Softball @ LJHS - Tuesday (8/4) - 9-11am

Baseball @ CEL - Tuesday (8/4) - 4-6pm

Cross Country (WLB) @ Memorial Park- Wednesday (8/5) beginning at 8am

Make sure you bring your own mask, water bottle/drink and equipment. We prefer players not share helmets and bats to reduce the spread of Covid-19.

Make sure you have a current physical on file in the office and remember to pay the $25 activity fee.

post_text:
The CEL Board of Education approved the district's Return to School Plan. It is a guide for the 2020-2021 school year that will continue to be updated with the most current guidelines. Families have the choice of either in-person learning or a remote learning option. Parents must register their child for either option. If you have not registered your child(ren), registration packets can be picked up in the foyer or can be printed from the website (click Student Registration tab). Please register your child(ren) by July 31.

Please read the plan carefully. If you have any questions, please contact the office.

As always, we appreciate your support and patience as we navigate these unprecedented times. We are committed to creating a positive and safe environment for students and staff and are ready to kick off the school year.

You can find the plan at www.cel61.com

Chester-East Lincoln District #61
July 16 at 7:01 PM ·

Attention CEL Families:

We are working on our return to school plan and hope to share it with our families when it is ready. Currently, we are planning for in-person instruction Monday-Friday from 8:05 to 1:30. In addition, we are investigating an online curriculum for families who feel a remote learning option is a better fit for their student(s). As a reminder, in-person instruction does require students to wear a face mask. With either option, please register your student.

Registration packets may be picked up in the foyer (Monday - Friday from 8:30 - 3:00) or printed from our website (www.cel61.com). In-person registration for new students and anyone needing assistance is July 20th (12:00 - 7:00) and July 21st (8:30 - 3:30).

We are receiving updates on a regular basis and will continue to provide information as it changes. We appreciate your continued support and patience. We are excited to kick off the new school year with your student(s)!

If you have any questions, please contact the office (office@cel61.com or 217-732-4136).

post_text: TODAY IS THE LAST DAY to order your supply boxes! Don't miss out!!!
shared_text:
Chester-East Lincoln District #61
May 31 at 3:54 PM ·

LAST CHANCE - and DUE DATE CHANGE!

2020-2021 School Supplies
Don’t forget to order your school supplies for the 2020-2021 school year! Ordering through our account simplifies school shopping for you and is super easy! All you have to do is go to www.shopttkits.com and enter our account number (8373). You will then choose the grade level for your child and complete the order! The school supplies will come to CEL and be ready for your child to start the 2020-2021 school year! In addition, there are two add-ons you can take advantage of if you need them (headphones for 2nd/3rd graders and calculator for 7th/8th grades). If you have those already, you can skip that part! DEADLINE for ordering school supply boxes is June 5th (it has been extended)! Please email Mrs. Aper (aaper@cel61.com) if you have any questions.

post_text: Although I didn't get my invitation - what a fun idea! Great Job Mrs. Scott! ;-)
shared_text:
Lincoln Daily News
May 1 at 10:57 AM ·

05/01/2020 - TOP PIX IN COMMUNITY
Last Sunday Jenelle Scott (center) and her parents Jan and Mike Brosamer were on hand to assist sister and daughter Marci Eads of Mama's Arcade in putting together a truckload of food for the OACF Sunday lunch.

While waiting to help out, the trio was working on another project. Scott is a teacher at Chester-East Lincoln School. With school not in session right now, Scott, like many other teachers, is working to find creative ways to stay in touch with her students. On Sunday, the three were putting bags of microwave popcorn into envelopes to be sent to each of Scott's students.

Scott invited her kids to pop the corn and settle in to watch a movie with her. While they were all in different locations, they would still be able to do something together. Scott uses Zoom to meet with her students, and the movie they are going to watch together will be played during the class Zoom meeting today.

Photo by Karen Hargis

post_text:
Governor Pritzker has officially announced that schools will remain closed the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Although this is not the way we wanted to end the school year, and we miss your children dearly, we must take this challenging time and make the best of it. We will continue our remote learning and strive for growth while keeping the social-emotional well-being of our students and families at the forefront.

Students - we love you, miss you, and expect that you continue to work hard and make good choices. Make us proud even when we aren’t with you at school.

post_text:
As you have been hearing, the COVID-19 circumstances are changing every hour. This includes information we are receiving from the Illinois State Board of Education (ISBE), Illinois Department of Public Health, and the Regional Office of Education. We have been strongly advised to prepare for the possibility of a long-term school closure. In the event this happens, ISBE has been communicating the expectations that learning will continue in the form of e-learning (Alternative Learning Days) at home.

These days will mirror the Alternative Learning Days we have in place, with some adjustments as we are continuing to brainstorm ways to improve instruction during this uncertain time. In order to help us plan for a long-term closure and know what resources our families have at home, we are asking that you complete this short survey (link below) to help us gather information.

CLICK BELOW FOR THE SURVEY.

Thank you for your time and understanding.
